        Out of pure instinct I reached for my sidearm, the trusty clue banana... but alas, I had left it on the dash of my car.  <br/><br/>VonHeffer sat at the table, a nervous twitch ran through his neck every few minutes.  A coffee lover I see.  Excellent.<br/><br/>"Well, let's break this down." I began.  "We have a rogue ex-employee, a stolen laptop, stolen keys, and you are possibly under some kind of surveillance?"<br/><br/>"Yes." VonHeffer said in between nervous twitches.<br/><br/>"Dave, let's go for a walk." I said as I grabbed Dave by the arm.<br/><br/>We excused ourselves and walked outside.<br/><br/>"What's up?" Dave asked.<br/><br/>"This doesn't feel right." I said."What do you mean?" Dave questioned me as he sat down on a bench outside the restaurant.<br/><br/>"Well, he's either leaving something out, or making some of this up.  Who throws surveillance on a previous employer like this?  The ex-employee has all the cards.  The non-compete is going to be hard to win in court, we both know that.   If TouchThemSoft is responsible for the break-ins, what were they after besides the keys and the laptop?  What do the keys go to?  What's on the laptop?" I asked.<br/><br/>"You want to do this by the numbers and see what happens?  We're talking some serious billable hours here Chief." Dave said, dollar signs blazing in his eyes.<br/><br/>"You read my mind.  Let's sign the agreements and roll over to their HQ.  We need to talk to their legal folks and find out if they have ever done any type of risk assessments.  And I want to know what was on that laptop." I said.<br/><br/>"Sounds good - but what do you want to do about this little surveillance issue?" Dave asked me as he lit up a cigarette.<br/><br/>"We can ghost chase.  Call Mikey - put him on VonHeffer for a few days, take some pictures, you know... by the numbers.  Have him do a covert on him though... if someone close to VonHeffer is 'in' on something I don't want Mikey compromised.  We'll see if someone is really following VonHeffer." I replied.<br/><br/>"Done deal Chief." Dave said as he put out his cigarette under his shoe.<br/><br/>'One last thing." I began.<br/><br/>"Yeah Chief?" Dave responded.<br/><br/>"Until we know this whole thing isn't rotten, mum is the word on operational plans.  We discuss nothing with the client." I demanded.<br/><br/>"Your gut really bothering you on this one Chief?" Dave asked.<br/><br/>"Something besides the coffee?  Yes."<br/><br/>(Aside)<br/><br/>Pick out the holes in VonHeffer's story.  What was bothering my gut?  Coffee is not an allowed answer.<br/><br/>(/Aside)
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer marginleftgutter">
            <hr/>
    <table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
        <tr>
            <td>
