                <div class="floatleft" style="margin-top:-2px; margin-right:10px"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111232947/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/"><div class="userimage-defaulttiny"></div></a>
</div>


<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130111232947/http://it.toolbox.com/people/unknownuser/" class="size11">Unknown User</a>

<!---->

				
<span class="size11 darkgray">Jun 9, 2004</span>
                
                

            </div>
			<span class="anthracite size13" contentbodystyle="Anthracite">Assuming (for a start) that the client is telling the truth - or most of it - the first two break-ins, at the office and his home, may have been for the purpose of planting something, as opposed to taking something.  Microphones and cameras come to mind.  The Harmonica bug is an oldie but goodie.  We have to take the client's word for it at this point about the wonderful management and happy customers.  What would be on an Admin Assistant's laptop that could prove damaging to the company?  How much technical access was the Admin given?  Locks can be changed, so the loss of the keys isn't really significant.  The money and jewelry could be nothing more than a smoke screen.  What's got me confused is what did you spot that I didn't?  Your antennae went up real quick shortly after you sat down and he started talking and getting nervous.  Could the whole thing be a sham to cover for something else that's not right?  Like cooked books or under-performing technology?</span>
		</div>
           
